ORDER OF REMAND: On October 25, 2017, this Court issued an Order to Show Cause why this action should not be remanded for lack of subject matter jurisdiction. ECF No. 3. The parties responded on November 1, 2017. ECF Nos. 4, 5. Plaintiff filed a supplementary declaration on November 3, 2017. ECF No. 8. (As further set forth in this Order.) The Court having found that it lacks subject matter jurisdiction, this case is REMANDED to state court. 28 U.S.C. § 1447. The Clerk of Court is respectfully directed to close this case. ORDER: Defendant removed this action to federal court on October 23, 2017, on the basis of diversity jurisdiction, pursuant to 28 U.S.C. § 1332(a). The Court has reviewed the Complaint and the Notice of Removal to ascertain the basis for assertion of subject matter jurisdiction in this Court. Defendant, a New York citizen, removed this complaint to a New York federal court. Notice of Removal, ECF No. 1. Moreover, a defendant has 30 days after receipt by or service on the defendant of the initial pleading to file a notice of removal. 28 U.S.C. § 1446(b). Plaintiff filed the complaint and served Defendant on September 14, 2017. See Compl. Defendant acknowledges receiving a copy of Plaintiff's summons and complaint on September 21, 2017. Notice of Removal paragraph 2, ECF No. 1. However, the affidavit of service states that Defendant was served on September 27, 2017. ECF No. 1, Ex. A at 71. Defendant filed a notice of removal on October 23, 2017. Therefore, it is hereby ORDERED, that the parties must, no later than November 1, 2017, show cause in writing as to why removal was proper, and as further set forth in this order. (Signed by Judge Andrew L. Carter, Jr on 10/25/2017) (ap) (Entered: 10/25/2017)
